This is barbecue!
Without a doubt the best beef brisket that I have found west of the Mississippi and the mild sauce is just right for my palate.
The side dish that I had with my beef brisket sandwich tasted homemade and it was called baked potato salad.
Like any good bbq restaurant, Bryan's serves sweet tea, too.
Bryan's sells their beef brisket by the pound at a reasonable price and I intend to return soon to buy a couple of pounds and a bottle of their mild sauce.
Didn't try it, but I noticed several people around me eating bbq'd chicken and the aroma was mouth-watering.
The decor is keeping with the West/Southwest and I liked it, which includes things like vintage western movie posters and an old cowboy movie showing on a big screen.
It appears that Bryan's is about to start patio seating, which will be nice to eat outside.
My only complaint last night was that the live music was too loud for a small restaurant.
Friends with me complained, too, that we couldn't talk to each other over the music.
Finally, I noted on the back of their business card that they have a website, which is www.bryansbbq.com.
The biggest compliment that I can give Bryan's is that I can't wait to go back SOON!

