Well thought out flavor profiles, even the smallest items have attention to details.
I'd go back again and enjoyed my first experience.
I was enjoying a day of meandering around Cave Creek and was getting hungry for lunch.
Walked past Bryan's and caught a wiff of their wonderful smokehouse smell.
It built on me and a block past I turned around and decided to try it.
Saw several local office folk going in so I followed them.
The pulled pork sandwich was excpetional, great texture and flavor to the meat.
While I waited for my lunch I tried the two types of sauces from the condiments dispensers; normal and hot.
Alone, the sauce flavors seemed to lean too far towards tomato-ey for what I imagined BBQ sauce should be.
But when my meal came the flavor spectrum melded with the pork wonderfully.
Lesson learned:  Don't judge the BBQ sauce flavors alone, they gotta hit the meat.
My side was the potato salad, which I'd normally not think much of.
The Chef had used Baked Potato chunks which added a nice base flavor, then mixed them in with a thick, creamy dill sauce.
The baked tones complimented the herb and cream flavors so very well.
OMG it was tasty, I ended up finger licking that stuff out of the ramikan.
On the negative side, they serve lunch sandwiches in a basket lined with lightweight paper.
If any sauce gets on the paper it starts to get weak and can end up in your food.
Not  aproblem if you're a clean and neat BBQ consumer, but who is?
At one point I pulled a little bit of paper out of my mouth that had attached itself to my wet sandwich.
yuk.
Also, my bill showed that Cave Creek is hitting folks up with 10.27% sales tax.
Yowza, that hurts but it can't be helped.

